<TEXT>
retired adm robert bostwick carney planner 
of key pacific naval battles in world war ii and first chief of 
naval operations for president eisenhower died of cardiac arrest 
at his home monday he was 95 
carney chief of staff to adm william bull halsey was 
awarded the navy cross for his role in planning us operations in 
the battle of leyte gulf in october 1944 a battle in which 60 
japanese ships were sunk at a cost of seven us vessels he later 
headed the group that planned the invasion of okinawa 
among other assignments after the war he served as commander in 
chief of nato forces in southern europe 
as chief of naval operations from 1953 to 1955 carney was 
charged with holding down budgets following the korean war 
carney is survived by a daughter four grandchildren and eight 
greatgrandchildren his wife of 71 years grace craycroft carney 
died last december and a son retired marine corps brig gen 
robert b carney died in 1983 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

