<DOCNO> AP900625-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mayor marion barry ordered fourday layoffs in 
august for some 26000 district of columbia employees to offset a 
projected 95 million budget deficit city officials said on monday 
once again city employees are being asked to bite the bullet 
for mismanagement of the city government said david a schlein 
head of the local chapter of the american federation of government 
employees the furloughs are not a solution for what is clearly a 
longterm problem 
the union represents nearly 6000 members of the citys 
48000member work force 
the furlough package reviewed by barry over the weekend is 
scheduled to take effect in august city administrator carol 
thompson said 
the fiscal package includes new taxes on public utilities and 
commercial property owners and spending cuts in human services job 
training and other government programs 
employees will take four days of unpaid leave on a staggered 
schedule designed to minimize the impact on the daytoday 
operations the furlough would not affect police fire and 
correctional officers or employees at dc general hospital and 
other roundthe clock operations district officials said the 
public school system and other independent agencies also will not 
be affected 
the administration has proposed reducing spending in the citys 
31 billion operating budget by 45 million while the proposed 
new taxes would raise about 40 million for the fiscal year the 
furlough would save an estimated 4 million according to officials 
</TEXT>
