<TEXT>
a ku klux klan leader says he hopes a challenge 
of a georgia law that bans masks in public will produce more 
members and more donations 
a lot of people told us theyd be happy to join if they could 
remain anonymous said dave holland grand dragon of the southern 
knights of the kkk 
with them its possible wed have enough financial 
contributions to run people for office 
the 1951 law was struck down may 25 by a judge who said it 
violated a klansmans right to free speech the klansman had staged 
a masked oneman demonstration at a courthouse and was arrested on 
the misdemeanor 
the state appealed the judges ruling to the georgia supreme 
court which will hear arguments in september the law which 
carries up to a 1000 fine or a year in jail is being enforced in 
the meantime 
some who monitor hate groups fear a resurgence in klan strength 
and violence if klansmen are allowed to wear masks 
the fear is unwarranted holland insisted 
the people who would only join a protest anonymously would be 
local businessmen school teachers police officers people who 
would not carry out acts of violence he said last week 
danny levitas executive director of the center for democratic 
renewal which monitors hate groups called gwinnett county judge 
howard cooks ruling a major setback for civil rights activists 
the law forbids people from concealing their identity on public 
property it exempts holiday costumes gas masks for safety reasons 
or sports masks 
authors of the law said it was intended to destroy the klan 
the judge said the law was vague and too broad he agreed with 
the klan that its members could face persecution for their racist 
views if they did not have the protection of hoods and masks 
the southern knights of the kkk refuses to say how many members 
it has or discuss its finances 
david fuller the assistant solicitor who argued the case said 
violence would increase if klan members identities were protected 
it goes against everything thats right to give constitutional 
protection to a group thats sworn to accomplish their goals 
through unconstitutional means he said 
shade miller jr the klansman who was arrested in february for 
wearing a mask testified he feared for his safety and his familys 
if his klan affiliation were widely known 
i could lose my job my family might be in danger if 
people knew i was a klansman miller testified 
levitas said he has no data on how many klan activities in the 
last 10 years were committed in mask 
but he cited a 1983 incident in tallapoosa in which six men in 
klan masks broke into the home of an interracial couple and beat 
the husband as he helped his daughter with her homework four klan 
members were convicted on federal charges 
</TEXT>
