<DOCNO> AP900625-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
loggers in this olympic peninsula town 
have always known that the supply of huge ancient trees they depend 
on would start to run out some day they just didnt expect it this 
summer 
and if you had told them their whining chain saws and rumbling 
log trucks would be silenced by a fluffy 22ounce owl they 
probably would have laughed themselves right off a stump 
nobodys laughing now in neilton its one of dozens of pacific 
northwest towns suddenly facing economic ruin during what was 
supposed to be the timber industrys biggest boom in a decade 
the us fish and wildlife service on friday declared the 
northern spotted owl a threatened species under the endangered 
species act saying the bird might become extinct if its habitat in 
oldgrowth forests is not protected 
officials plan to hold off releasing a protection plan for the 
owl until later this week but under one scenario proposed earlier 
this year by a team of federal scientists timber harvests could be 
reduced by nearly half in the oldgrowth national forests of 
washington oregon and northern california 
those bans could cost 28000 jobs in the region over 10 years 
and tear apart timber towns with increased rates of violence 
divorce and suicide a federal study predicts 
neilton a tightly knit village of 400 surrounded by the olympic 
national forest has felt the pinch since january 1989 when the 
us forest service began slowing down timber sales to protect 
nesting areas of the secretive owl in anticipation of preservation 
measures 
existing contracts have kept some neilton loggers in business 
but most of those will run out this summer forest service 
officials said the agency scrambled to find a few oldgrowth 
parcels outside critical owl habitats for cutting this fall but 
loggers say those trees will keep them working only a few months 
one mill that produces cedar shingles for roofing already has 
closed here and another is struggling to find enough raw material 
school enrollment has declined 12 percent since september 
almost every house in town has a sign in the window proclaiming 
this family supported by timber dollars but many residents 
fear theyll soon be replaced by for sale signs 
its been pretty slim and i know its going to get slimmer 
said stanley metcalf 52 who now runs only two of his six 
loghauling trucks everybody in town is worried about their 
homes their families their businesses 
in some timber towns worry has turned to anger loggers have 
rallied in noisy protests from redding calif to aberdeen wash 
environmentalists consider the northwests ancient forests 
precious national resources that clean the air and trap flood 
waters all while providing opportunities for solace and recreation 
they say the towering evergreens 1000 years and older anchor 
a complex ecosystem that supports a diversity of wildlife absent in 
younger forests 
we have strong scientific evidence that an indicator of the 
health of the ecosystem the northern spotted owl is in very grave 
peril and that tells us that the ecosystem is in grave peril 
said melanie rowland an attorney for the wilderness society 
but charlie miller who has been in the logging business for 40 
years sees the big trees differently 
theyre overripe he said those trees should have been 
logged years ago our forest is just like a corn field in nebraska 
when that corn field is ripe youve got to cut it 
forty years ago miller had plenty of support for his views in 
1952 a forest service researcher called the ancient forests 
biological deserts and foresters saw nothing wrong with 
cutting old trees that had slowed their growth to make way for new 
stands of rapidly growing trees 
the philosophy fit well with commercial interests which valued 
the oldgrowth trees for their tight grain durability and lack of 
knots 
oldgrowth forests on private lands disappeared first after 
world war ii cutting on the northwests 12 national forests 
increased to fill the gap 
concerns about overharvesting surfaced in the late 1960s about 
the same time as researchers discovered that ancient forests were 
hardly biological deserts 
but the cutting continued 
since the early 1970s environmental groups pressured the fish 
and wildlife service to declare the owl threatened after years of 
delays lawsuits finally forced the agency to take a closer look at 
the owl population 
today nobody knows exactly how much remains of the west coasts 
original 17 million acres of oldgrowth forest federal estimates 
range from 32 million to 71 million acres scattered in patches up 
and down the pacific coast and estimates by industry and 
environmentalists vary even more 
and researchers dont know how many owls there are but they 
estimate the owl has lost 80 percent of its habitat since 1800 
even without the owl recent developments have already reduced 
the amount of national forest oldgrowth timber available to 
loggers additions to the wilderness preservation system have taken 
land out of logging and this month the forest service announced 
plans to reduce logging by 46 percent in the mount bakersnoqualmie 
national forest washingtons largest national forest 
this is public land and that is what the timber industry is 
forgetting said rowland the wilderness society attorney i 
bridle when they say it is their forest it simply is not 
as the region becomes more urbanized and diversified whats 
best for the timber industry is no longer necessarily whats best 
for the northwest she said logging and milling account for just 6 
percent of total employment in oregon 2 percent in washington and 
less than onehalf percent in california according to state 
officials 
its understandable why congress would not worry about the loss 
of 28000 jobs over such a large region said bill pickell head of 
the washington state contract loggers association 
but the jobs to be lost are concentrated in isolated towns 
which often have no way to replace them he said 
well have appalachia west out here pickell said 
state officials in washington and oregon are urging federal 
agencies to phase in any logging bans to let the industry adjust to 
lessdesirable young trees there have also been calls for federal 
aid to the loggers 
environmental reforms do not come free said rep ron wyden 
dore working families dont have the resources to prepare 
for changes forced by new environmental laws there is a real moral 
obligation for the government to assist those families 
president bush disagrees he said earlier this month that while 
he is concerned about timber workers he would oppose federal help 
for job retraining 
other relief may be on the way congress is considering measures 
to restrict or ban exports of raw timber thereby increasing the 
supply available to local mills 
but at this point loggers have little patience for government 
promises said neilton resident duane sim and the fight could get 
even nastier 
im not going to say what were going to do sim said but 
you can bet were not going to just roll over 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david foster is the aps northwest regional 
reporter based in seattle 
</TEXT>
