foreign secretary raul manglapus told 
career filipino diplomats today that he seeks to revive the 
countrys ties with the hispanic world so they must master spanish 
if they wish to advance 
in a directive to foreign service employees published in local 
papers manglapus said that in requiring knowledge of spanish the 
philippines is going back to a language that will restore us to 
our family of nations that will provide us with the backing we 
need 
we are going back to a language that is no longer a language 
of the oppressors said manglapus who is fluent in english and 
spanish today mostly in latin america it is the language of 
revolution of social change 
he said the widespread use of english identified the philippines 
with the united states but that in the united nations and other 
world forums not everybody is in favor of the us when it comes 
to voting 
spain ruled the philippines for 350 years until it lost the 
colony to the americans during the spanishamerican war in 1898 
but spanish was never as widely spoken among the indigenous 
population as it was in spains colonies in latin america 
after 1898 the americans introduced english which remains an 
official language along with filipino a malayopolynesian language 
based on tagalog 
spanish is no longer a required course of study in philippine 
schools and relatively few of the 60 million filipinos speak it 
fluently 
but the vocabularies of tagalog and other philippine languages 
contain many words of spanish origin 
