nearly 30 obscene phone calls to her and 10 to her husband within a 
twoweek period allen said shes still frightened of him 
berendzen 51 was sentenced in may to 30 days in jail for each 
count but the sentence was suspended pending good behavior and 
continued outpatient treatment at johns hopkins hospital in 
baltimore 
according to his psychiatrists berendzens compulsive phone 
calls over a twoyear period were the result of severe sexual and 
emotional abuse as a child 
virginia state police spokeswoman lucy caldwell said the hot 
line might convince some victims to prosecute their harassers 
hopefully it will bring attention to the problem she said 
adding that victims no longer have to be quiet because theres 
someplace to turn 
since installing her line allen has received almost 500 calls 
from people around the country who have experienced obscene phone 
harassment several of the calls she received were obscene 
allen said many of the callers heard about getcha during one of 
her several recent appearances on national television programs 
they wont go to work or to the store alone she said 
they cant sleep because their callers call them all night 
allen also has a post office box for inquiries she has received 
some obscene letters and dead flowers but overall she said she 
has been inundated with letters from people seeking help 
although she considers her hot line successful allens efforts 
to solicit donations have not gone as well 
the public is real willing to receive information but is not 
willing to support the group she said my goal was to help 
other people to keep the issue in the publics eye i thought 
it would be received better than it has been 
so far allen has received 18 in donations and has spent nearly 
900 of her own money for getcha if donations dont start coming 
in allen said she might have to drop the tollfree line but she 
said shell keep the post office box 
this is a lifetime venture she said 
allen plans to apply for grants from the national organization 
for women and the government to support her group and to lobby 
congress for tougher legislation against obscene callers 
