<TEXT>
nearly two decades after reform jews began 
accepting women as rabbis they are being asked to extend the same 
welcome to homosexuals 
a resolution in support of homosexual rabbis was scheduled for a 
vote today at the central conference of american rabbis and it was 
expected to pass 
the reform movement has more than 15 million jews in the united 
states led by about 1560 reform rabbis it is the largest of the 
three main branches of judaism in this country 
the movement accepted women as rabbis beginning in 1972 the 
acceptance of homosexuals would be a major break from 4000 years 
of jewish tradition 
a 17member committee has prepared and recommended for approval 
a resolution that says homosexuals are as qualified as 
heterosexuals to lead congregations 
jewish law embodied in the torah and other texts condemns 
homosexuality as an abomination but out of concern for human 
dignity one is permitted to violate the prohibitions of torah 
said rabbi samuel karff of houston conference president and a 
member of the committee 
about 500 rabbis are attending the fourday conference which 
ends wednesday 
the conservative jewish movement has had women rabbis since 
1985 but it does not openly accept homosexual rabbis orthodox 
jews the third major branch oppose ordination of women or 
homosexuals as forbidden by jewish law 
judaisms smaller reconstructionist movement and the unitarian 
universalist church openly accept homosexual clergy and some other 
christian denominations approve ordination of homosexuals if they 
remain celibate 
the committee headed by rabbi selig salkowitz of union temple 
in new york city arrived at its conclusion after a fouryear study 
the committee urges that all rabbis regardless of sexual 
orientation be accorded the opportunity to fulfill the sacred 
vocation which they have chosen reads a draft of the resolution 
sexual orientation is irrelevant to the human worth of a person 
at the same time a majority of the committee affirmed that 
heterosexual marriage remains the ideal 
