<DOCNO> AP900625-0073 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide who 
the secretary of labor or a safety and health review board has 
the last word on what federal regulations require for onthejob 
safety 
the courts decision expected sometime next year will 
determine whether cfampi steel corp of pueblo colo must pay a 
10000 fine for not making sure the respirators given to coke oven 
workers fit them properly 
cfampi was fined in 1979 by the secretary of labor but the 
occupational safety and health review commission set aside the fine 
in 1986 
the secretary of labor had interpreted a regulation governing 
employee exposure to coke oven emissions as a testing standard 
that imposes an obligation by employers to make sure respirators 
fit 
but the commission interpreted the regulation as a training 
standard not requiring such employer assurances of proper fits 
cfampi produces coke a coal derivative to fuel the blast 
furnaces of its steel plant in pueblo 
the labor department in 1976 determined that coke oven emissions 
are cancercausing and issued safety standards limiting exposure 
to them the standard permits the use of respirators as one method 
of compliance 
cfampi was cited in 1977 for several coke emission violations and 
again in 1979 one of the labor department citations issued in 1979 
imposed the 10000 fine for willful violation of the 
respirator regulation 
an administrative law judge for the review commission upheld the 
citation but the commission reversed that judgment 
the 10th us circuit court of appeals last december ruled 
against the secretary of labor 
in the face of conflicting regulatory interpretations 
deference is properly accorded to the interpretation of the 
commission the appeals court said 
other appeals courts have reached the opposite conclusion 
the commission created under the occupational safety and health 
act of 1970 hears disputes over safety citations and penalties 
it does not have the power to review safety and health standards 
issued by the federal government that reviewing authority is held 
by federal appeals courts 
the case is dole vs occupational safety and health review 
commission 891541 
</TEXT>
