<DOCNO> AP900625-0077 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to revive a 
14yearold lawsuit by a texas oil refinerys black employees who 
say they are victims of racial discrimination 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that dismissed 
the suit against a union and gulf oil corp 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals in december threw out the 
1976 suit by employees at a gulf oil refinery in port arthur 
the appeals court said a federal judge who ruled against the 
workers was not clearly erroneous in deciding that revised 
seniority and promotion rules at the refinery did not discriminate 
intentionally against blacks 
the appeals court also upheld the judges findings that the 
seniority rules and promotion tests had legitimate business 
purposes even if unintentionally they disproportionately favored 
white workers 
the plant maintained a strictly segregated work force until the 
mid1950s with blacks in unskilled jobs and whites in skilled 
craft positions 
as that began to change the company in 1967 changed 
jobclassification rules in an agreement with the oil chemical and 
atomic workers international union 
gulf oil said the new rules were designed to streamline 
operations and promote efficiency blacks said the rules locked 
them into lowerranking jobs by promoting craft helpers most of 
them white into trainee positions ahead of blacks with more 
seniority 
the black workers also challenged the use of written tests 
revised in 1971 that had the effect of promoting whites 
disproportionately for example nearly every white worker who took 
the tests between 1971 and 1980 passed while only twothirds of 
the blacks passed 
the black employees said the tests were unrelated to job 
performance but gulf said statistics showed that those who did 
well on the tests also did well in their new jobs 
the 5th circuit court in dismissing the suit relied in part on 
a key supreme court ruling last year that makes it harder for 
workers to prove bias 
the appeals court said the high court ruling means that 
employers accused of bias can prevail merely by producing evidence 
not proof that the challenged practice serves in a significant 
way the legitimate employment goals of the employer 
the black workers also questioned whether the appeals court gave 
too broad an interpretation to another 1989 high court decision 
that limits the time frame for some bias suits 
in that ruling the justices said the deadline for filing a suit 
is determined by the date an allegedly biased seniority plan is 
adopted not when an individual worker is affected by the plan 
congress is seeking to overturn or modify both 1989 high court 
rulings as part of a legislative civil rights package the 
legislation is the subject of negotiations in the house and senate 
and with the bush administration 
the case is bernard vs gulf oil 891617 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

