<TEXT>
for joe cruzan and his family the 
legal fight to let their comatose daughter die is over now come 
the years of waiting while she lies attached to a hospital feeding 
tube 
the us supreme court barred the removal of her lifesustaining 
tube today in its first ruling in a righttodie case 
the court in a 54 decision said a states interest in 
preserving life may overcome the wishes of family members seeking 
to end the life of a patient in an irreversible comalike condition 
to the family the facts were painfully simple they wanted 
death to become a reality for 32yearold nancy who has been in a 
persistent vegetative state since a january 1983 car crash shes 
kept alive by a surgically implanted feeding tube at the missouri 
rehabilitation center in mount vernon 
doctors say she has no hope of recovery but could remain alive 
for many years 
a voice on the telephone answering machine at the home of joe 
and joyce cruzan in carterville mo said the family will have no 
response to the high courts decision until they have had time to 
analyze the ruling 
chief justice william h rehnquist writing the majority 
opinion said missouri may require clear and convincing proof 
that ms cruzan wants to die before allowing the withdrawal of 
lifesustaining treatment such evidence is lacking in ms cruzans 
case he said 
thats one of the arguments the state made which apparently 
the majority agrees with missouri attorney general william 
webster said 
webster reserved additional comment until he could review the 
ruling 
in a statement gov john ashcroft said he was grateful the 
court backed the states position he also said that our thoughts 
and prayers remain with the cruzan family 
