<TEXT>
a new word has quietly slipped into the 
vocabulary of doctors and scientists who are on the battle lines 
against aids optimism 
with 130000 already sick or dead and at least 1 million 
infected aids is a huge health problem in the united states but 
for the first time since the epidemic emerged almost a decade ago 
experts seem uniformly convinced that aids will someday and 
perhaps soon be brought under medical control 
researchers at the sixth international conference on aids which 
concluded sunday pointed to these hopeful signs 
the epidemic in the united states appears to be leveling off 
the number of new aids deaths is sharply lower than what 
researchers a few years ago had projected it would be by now 
many new drugs are in the works that will attack the aids virus 
at every stage of its life cycle combinations of medicines may be 
powerful tools for postponing or halting the development of aids in 
people infected with the virus hiv 
creating an aids vaccine to stop infections until recently 
considered a questionable prospect appears to be much more likely 
during the 1990s 
there is a fair amount of optimism with the current drugs and 
this will be added to when we have other drugs to combine with 
them said the conference chairman dr paul volberding of the 
university of california san francisco 
despite the positive developments during the past year no one 
is talking seriously about curing aids instead the goal is to 
turn hiv infection into a manageable chronic condition like 
diabetes or high blood pressure 
awesome obstacles remain 
the virus continues to move beyond its initial victims 
homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers 
in the united states women and children are increasingly 
becoming targets as hiv spreads through sex from men to women and 
in the womb from mothers to fetuses around the world perhaps 8 
million people are already infected and the epidemic still seems 
to be gaining momentum 
hiv is now part of the global environment and the global 
potential for hiv spread remains vast cautioned jonathan mann 
former head of the world health associations global program on 
aids 
the present is indeed gloomy but at this gathering more than 
any previous international aids meeting the researchers spoke of 
their successes and the chance that they will ultimately stop the 
epidemic 
one crucial weapon is a vaccine that will keep people who are 
still virus free from becoming infected more than 30 approaches to 
vaccine development are being studied half a dozen potential 
vaccines already are being tested on people or nearing that stage 
dr wayne koff head of vaccine development at the national 
institute on allergy and infectious diseases predicted that a 
vaccine should be ready for widespread use by the mid to late 
1990s 
in the past year we have cracked open the door of optimism 
he said in the next two to three years we will knock it down 
now only one drug azt is available for routine use while it 
does not cure aids it can prolong patients lives by a few months 
perhaps even more useful is its ability to forestall the start of 
aids in outwardly healthy people who are infected with hiv 
two similar drugs ddi and ddc are in the final stages of 
testing new research suggests that combinations of these drugs 
will be far more powerful inhibitors of the virus than any single 
medicine and dozens of new drugs are being tested 
researchers once predicted that the number of aids deaths would 
continue to grow sharply for years but to their surprise the 
epidemic began to flatten in 1986 and perhaps earlier 
no one knows precisely why it happened or whether the epidemic 
will pick up speed again however the introduction of azt and 
avoidance of risky habits that spread the disease probably 
contributed to the change 
doctors hope that all of these developments mean that the 
epidemic while far from over will soon lose some of its fierce 
power 
as dr jay levy of the university of california san francisco 
told the convention we have begun to see the horizon and we 
will get there 
</TEXT>
