<TEXT>
fang lizhi has said he is happiest pondering the 
mysteries of the universe it is this fascination with the unknown 
that led to his break with marxism and emergence as one of chinas 
most outspoken critics 
fangs research in cosmology the study of the universe and 
black hole physics won him international attention but a debate in 
that field several years ago forced the 54yearold astrophysicist 
to question his communist leaders 
former politburo member hu qiaomu had questioned the need to 
study cosmology since marxism already maintained the universe was 
infinite 
this is an open question right now fang replied in 
cosmology marxism is not right 
it was the first step in a process that led to the leaderships 
enmity and to fangs eventual flight to the us embassy to seek 
shelter from prosecution he was allowed to leave the embassy on 
monday after more than a year and he flew to britain 
fang became bestknown for his fearless advocacy of transforming 
the one party communist state into a freer society he was one of 
only a few chinese who dared to campaign publicly for democratic 
change before the popular uprising for freedom rocked beijing in 
the spring of 1989 
i like to speak freely fang said in an interview in 1988 
i think i just show we have the right of speech 
fang not only spoke with students and foreign reporters but also 
tried to reach a broader tougher audience of chinese 
some people think china doesnt need democracy but i think 
human rights are basic fang told actors scientists and business 
leaders at a gathering in february 1989 for human rights to be 
realized first of all famous people must take a stand 
fang the son of a postal clerk in hangzhou was admitted to 
beijing university in 1952 at age 16 to study theoretical physics 
and nuclear physics 
after studying nuclear reactor theory he became one of chinas 
pioneer researchers in laser theory 
he burst into political prominence during prodemocracy student 
demonstrations of 198687 authorities alleged his speeches to 
students at the university of science and technology where he was 
vice president incited unrest 
chinas leaders kicked him out of the communist party and fired 
him from his university post although the demonstrations died 
down fang refused to be silenced and he received letters of 
support from across the country almost daily 
in january 1989 fang called for the release of all political 
prisoners and urged intellectuals to join together to work for 
human rights 
the following month when president bush was visiting beijing 
fang was barred from attending a banquet held by the united states 
china said that inviting him was an insult 
china had accused fang and his wife li shuxian of leading the 
huge prodemocracy protests last spring although the two did not 
take an active role 
after the june 4 1989 military crackdown on the 
demonstrations in which hundreds and perhaps thousands of people 
died fang and li sought refuge in the us embassy american 
diplomats refused to turn them over to chinese authorities 
while being sheltered at the embassy fang and li declined to 
talk with reporters and the embassy refused to answer nearly all 
questions about them 
in november however fang wrote a letter accepting a human 
rights award 
remember that in the current climate of terror it may well be 
that those who are most terrified are those who have just finished 
the killing he wrote 
we may be forced to live under a terror today but we have no 
fear of tomorrow the murderers are not only fearful today they 
are even more terrified of tomorrow 
