<TEXT>
the righttodie ruling by the us supreme 
court removes some clinical choices from doctors and family and 
puts the burden of assuring death with dignity solely on one 
person the person who is dying 
though the ruling applies directly only to missouri which 
already has restrictive laws experts believe medical communities 
in many states may generally apply the principles expressed in the 
case decided monday 
the result some said is that if there is any question about 
what a person in a vegetative state would want done the doctors 
may choose to keep the patient alive no matter what the family says 
there are an estimated 10000 americans who are beyond recall 
from coma more are added annually with accidents and illnesses 
and with the increasing skill of medicine to maintain life 
many people in such a state are allowed to die when doctors say 
there is no hope of recovery and the families believe the patient 
would choose such a death 
i think the whole atmosphere in medicine will shift toward a 
more conservative ethical position on providing life support 
said william t reich a professor for bioethics at georgetown 
university hospital this will put a lot of pressure on people to 
sign a living a will or to put something in writing to make 
certain their wishes are known 
dr terry walman a member of the medical ethics committee at 
johns hopkins hospital in baltimore said the ruling suggested that 
those who want to make decisions about their terminal care can no 
longer informally leave it to others 
they must take some action either in writing or appointing 
someone to act in their behalf he said if they dont do that 
then in states with laws like missouri they are in danger of not 
having their wishes followed 
dr david p thomasma the director of the medical humanities 
program at loyola university in chicago said that in a usual 
hospital setting doctors and families talk about what should be 
done about a patient in an irreversible state of coma 
we trust family members and guardians unless there is reason 
to believe they are not trustworthy thomasma said 
often the family members call on memories of what the patient 
said and thought before the accident or injury and try to 
interpret from these recollections what the patient would want 
traditionally the common law in most states permitted 
guardians to make such decisions thomasma said 
for patients whose breathing depends on hightech support he 
said it is universally understood and accepted that the plug can 
be pulled if there is no sign of life in the brain 
but as in the missouri case decided monday the withholding of 
food and nutrition is seen as another issue 
nancy cruzan now 32 suffered severe brain damage in a 1983 car 
accident her parents authorized the use of a feeding tube in the 
hope her condition would improve but later requested that the tube 
be removed ms cruzan who breathes on her own has been in a 
comalike condition for seven years 
the fluid and nutrition issue is the most difficult for people 
because a person is not dying of the underlying disease or injury 
but death is the result of dehydration or starvation thomasma 
said 
the ruling left intact the concept that comatose patients can be 
deprived of food and water unto death but it now permits states to 
pass laws that would require a higher level of proof of the 
patients wishes 
this is the first time that the court has said that such clear 
proof is needed said walman an anesthesiologist and lawyer 
it makes it much harder now for the family to speak for the 
patients 
a head injury stroke or drug reaction could send anyone forever 
into unconsciousness but few people actually take formal action 
ahead of time to make sure their medical wishes are followed 
dr joanne lynn director of aging studies at george washington 
university said that even if people do write out their wishes 
ahead of time it would be unlikely that they could describe 
precisely the medical circumstance of their final illness 
without a precise description she said under the new ruling 
patients in states with laws such as missouri would have to be kept 
alive 
under the missouri ruling a person who is suffering horribly 
but who is incompetent must be kept alive by the healthcare 
giver if possible lynn said 
