<TEXT>
federal and state animalhealth authorities 
are cooperating in a nationwide alert for signs of mad cow 
disease which has stricken britains cattle industry the 
agriculture department said monday 
the disease bovine spongiform encephalopathy or bse was not 
known to exist in the united states said james w glosser 
administrator of the departments animal health and inspection 
service 
the disease attacks the central nervous system and is fatal to 
cattle there has been no scientific evidence that it is a human 
health hazard officials said 
the agency glosser said has barred the importation of live 
cattle from britain since july 1989 
also over 150 federal and state veterinarians constantly 
conduct field investigations of suspicious diseases and report 
their findings to us glosser said 
the national surveillance program will include usda animal 
health officials state veterinary diagnostic laboratories and iowa 
state university 
initially he said laboratories in at least 16 states will be 
cooperating in the program california iowa illinois indiana 
kentucky maryland michigan minnesota missouri new york ohio 
pennsylvania tennessee virginia washington and wisconsin 
glosser said other states also have requested to be included so 
laboratory specimens may be received from other sources as well 
cattle affected by bse may suffer changes in temperament such 
as nervousness or aggression thus accounting for it sometimes 
being called mad cow disease 
other symptoms include abnormal posture lack of coordination 
and difficulty in rising reduced milk production loss of body 
weight despite continued appetite and eventually death 
confirmation of the disease is possible only through postmortem 
examination of the animals brain there is no test to detect the 
disease in a live animal 
</TEXT>
