<TEXT>
the national endowment for the arts opposes 
federal support for obscenity as the antithesis of art but its 
judges panels base their grantmaking decisions primarily on 
esthetic and artistic quality the government arts agencys chief 
lawyer said monday 
the lawyer julie davis said the arts endowment expects to 
issue guidelines by july 13 that will interpret controversial 
legislation that forbids endowment support for obscene art to 
help artists receiving federal grants comply with the law 
ms davis said the guidelines generally would embrace the 
supreme courts longstanding obscenity test that test outlined in 
a 1973 decision says material is obscene if it depicts sexual 
conduct in a patently offensive manner appeals to prurient 
interest and lacks serious literary artistic political or 
scientific value 
ms davis testified at a daylong hearing of an independent 
12member commission created by congress last fall to review the 
endowments grantmaking procedures and consider whether a 
different standard should apply to governmentsubsidized art than 
to privately financed art 
the commission which will meet again in late july hopes to 
report to congress before the group legally expires on sept 30 
the panel was appointed by president bush and the house and 
senate leadership and is headed by former white house counsel 
leonard garment and john brademas a former democratic congressman 
from indiana who is president of new york university 
congress established the commission at the same time it 
prohibited the arts endowment from spending federal funds on any 
artistic works that may be considered obscene including 
depictions of sex acts homoeroticism sadomasochism or sexual 
exploitation of children and which lack any serious literary 
artistic political or scientific value 
the ban was imposed as a result of criticism by conservative 
lawmakers led by sen jesse helms rnc of an 
endowmentsupported exhibits of sexually explicit photographs by 
the late robert mapplethorpe and works by artist andres serrano 
that included an image of a crucifix submerged in urine 
the furor over obscene art has thrust the arts endowment an 
independent federal agency with a 171 million budget into the 
biggest crisis of its 25year history the house and senate are 
bracing for major floor battles over legislation intended to extend 
the neas life and what restrictions might be imposed on artists 
receiving endowment grants 
ms davis said endowment chairman john e frohnmayer believes 
that obscenity is the antithesis of art and has vowed to block 
nea financial support from arts projects that might be deemed 
obscene 
she said the nea panels of outside experts who take preliminary 
action on grant applications base their decisions primarily on 
questions of artistic merit and not on the content of art works 
judgments of whether a grant project might violate the 
antiobscenity law are left to frohnmayer and his senior advisers 
she said 
about 100 recipients of arts endowment grants this year have 
signed the neas antiobscenity pledge under protest endowment 
officials say six artists or arts institutions have rejected nea 
grants rather than sign the pledge 
the endowment has awarded 2000 grants so far this year 
