<TEXT>
prosecutors and defense lawyers argued in 
federal court monday over whether genetic fingerprints should 
be used in a weapons trial of three hells angels accused in the 
slaying of a record store clerk 
lawyers for steven yee mark verdi and john ray bonds told us 
magistrate james carr that the fbis dna testing program is 
unreliable and should not be used as scientific evidence 
carr will rule on whether dna tests should be admissible in the 
case it is the first time the admissibility of dna evidence has 
been argued in the federal court system and carrs ruling could 
establish an important precedent 
the hearing which began monday is expected to last more than a 
month 
the three motorcycle gang members face murder and federal 
weapons charges in the death of david hartlaub a sandusky record 
store clerk who was shot on feb 27 1988 they are being tried on 
the weapons offenses before the murder charges 
assistant us attorney michael rae head of an organized crime 
task force argued that the fbis program is an accurate way of 
analyzing whether a person was involved in a crime 
rae said genetic scientists and biologists would testify that 
the fbis program and dna testing in general is reliable 
genetic fingerprinting involves examining live human tissue such 
as skin and hair or body fluid such as blood or saliva to 
determine a persons genetic code the pattern is found in dna 
deoxyribonucleic acid which forms the basic material in the 
chromosome of the cell nucleus 
some scientists say the odds are as high as 30 billion to 1 that 
any two people outside of identical twins will have the same dna 
pattern 
dwight adams who works in the fbis dna analysis unit told 
carr that dna has been used successfully to determine whether a 
person has been involved in a crime but he acknowledged that 
unlike fingerprints they cannot indicate with 100 percent 
certainty that samples taken from a crime scene came from a suspect 
all i can do is conclude that an individual is a possible 
contributor to that stain but i cannot say he is the sole 
contributor said adams who has a doctorate in biology 
prosecutors said dna tests conducted by the fbi show that bonds 
blood was found in hartlaubs van and in yees car they also said 
bonds was wounded by shrapnel during the shooting 
peter neufeld one of the defendants lawyers said scientists 
are divided over whether absolute matches can be made in criminal 
cases in which the dna is extracted from small amounts of tissue 
neufeld and his partner barry scheck also argued that genetic 
matching often includes subjective judgments on the part of a 
technician 
prosecutors said hartlaub was shot as part of a hells angels 
initiation for bonds they said bonds mistakenly thought hartlaub 
was a member of the outlaws a rival motorcycle gang 
</TEXT>
