<TEXT>
the supreme courts decision to keep 
nancy cruzan alive should force the missouri legislature to return 
to the righttodie issue which stalled in this years session 
officials said monday 
the court said here you are states you may not want to 
deal with this but were going to dump it in your laps now deal 
with it said senate president pro tem james mathewson he 
predicted the issue will come up before the 1991 legislature which 
convenes in january 
in its 54 ruling the high court said missouri may require 
clear and convincing proof that a patient in a persistent 
vegetative state with no hope of recovery such as ms cruzan 
wants to die before allowing the withdrawal of lifesustaining 
treatment 
ms cruzan 32 has remained for seven years in a comalike 
condition her parents are attempting to get permission to remove 
her feeding tube 
righttodie legislation stalled in the missouri senate during 
the 1990 session proposals endorsed by ms cruzans father and 
state attorney general william webster would have allowed removal 
of food and water if three independent physicians agreed there was 
no chance of recovery after waiting for three years 
webster said the courts ruling leaves it up to individual 
states to set statutory guidelines on what defines clear and 
convincing proof the patient wants to die 
this decision has impact far beyond the borders of the state 
of missouri webster said state courts have been waiting for a 
definitive federal ruling but in this decision today theyve 
essentially said its up to the states he said 
we would like to change the law so that families with 
patients like nancy could receive relief and yet there would still 
be safeguards to protect against those that dont have the best 
interests of the patient at heart webster said 
missouri already is among the 41 states and the district of 
columbia that have living will laws which allow individuals to 
make their wishes about medical treatment known in advance of a 
crisis that may render them unable to speak 
the high court ruled that ms cruzan had not made her wishes 
known before she entered the vegetative state 
sen dennis smith who sponsored some of the righttodie 
legislation said the ruling gives impetus to those who think the 
state should address this very delicate and difficult issue to do 
nothing is to put in jeopardy people who may be in this situation 
an opponent of the legislation louis defeo of the missouri 
catholic conference said it seems the court has taken steps to 
protect the individual that third parties are not to be making 
these ultimate personal decisions 
webster said the catholic conferences opposition was important 
in defeating this years legislation but said he hoped a 
compromise could be reached in the next session 
