congress on monday approved and sent to the 
white house new amtrak legislation devoid of the railroad 
antitakeover provision that drew a veto from president bush 
the bill was approved by a voice vote first in the house and 
then in the senate 
the legislation caps federal subsidies for the governmentowned 
passenger railroad at 684 million in the fiscal year beginning 
oct 1 and at 712 million in fiscal 1992 
in vetoing an earlier version bush said he accepted the 
spending figures but objected to a plan which would have required 
interstate commerce commission approval of railroad takeovers by 
nonrailroad companies 
the house voted to override bushs veto but the senate narrowly 
failed to get the needed twothirds majority to enact the bill over 
his objections 
because the presidents concerns have been addressed the 
current version of the bill is acceptable to the administration 
the white house said in a statement monday 
