<TEXT>
china has ended the yearlong isolation of 
dissident fang lizhi in hopes of ending its own estrangement from 
the united states and other western nations 
astrophysicist fang and his wife li shuxian a physicist 
arrived in upper heyford a us base 60 miles west of london late 
monday on a us air force jet after the government allowed them to 
leave the us embassy where they had been living since june 1989 
beijing cited leniency in allowing the couple wanted by 
police as counterrevolutionary criminals to leave monday but the 
decision was based more on diplomatic than humanitarian concerns 
it was the latest and most important gesture aimed at returning 
to the good graces of the west 
china has been stunned by western condemnation of the military 
suppression of the prodemocracy movement last june that forced 
fang and his wife chinas leading advocates of democratic reform 
to seek refuge in the us embassy 
western nations suspended highlevel contacts invited chinese 
studying in their countries to stay and blocked governmental and 
world bank loans to china 
government spokesman yuan mu in an interview last week with 
japanese reporters acknowledged that restrictions on development 
loans had hurt he said china cannot put its trust in impractical 
selfwishes for better relations with the west 
china has made several diplomatic gestures this year directed at 
ending its ostracism it lifted martial law in beijing in january 
and ended more than a year of martial law in the tibetan capital of 
lhasa on may 1 
since december nearly 900 people arrested in connection with 
the prodemocracy protests last spring have been released the 
government has stressed that chinese students both in china and 
abroad will not be prosecuted merely for joining prodemocracy 
protests 
fangs release removes a major impediment to improved uschina 
relations which seriously deterioriated after the military 
crackdown 
relations have hit the bottom a foreign ministry official 
said monday they have no place to go but up 
he added however that china is puzzled by the tendency in 
the west to discount chinas goodwill gestures as cosmetic 
western critics say china in reality has done little to improve 
its human rights record they note that although martial law ended 
in beijing thousands of troops remain in the city to crush any 
attempt at political protest 
and although fang was allowed to leave the country many 
wellknown figures among them student leader wang dan political 
scientist liu xiaobo senior party official bao tong and political 
activist ren wanding face long prison terms as alleged 
counterrevolutionaries 
thousands who joined in the protests last year are still in jail 
without having been charged or tried 
fangs release was timed to coincide with debate in the us 
congress on giving china mostfavorednation trading status 
many members of congress citing chinas human rights record 
have opposed president bushs decision to extend the trade status 
which gives china low tariffs on exports to the united states 
resolution of the fang case also comes just before the western 
nations hold their annual summit in houston one question at the 
july summit will be whether to continue opposing loans to china by 
international financial organizations such as the world bank 
even before the decision to release fang cracks were appearing 
in western sanctions on china the bush administration has approved 
world bank loans on a human need basis and the bank has pushed 
ahead with 590 million in credit to china 
japanese foreign ministry officials indicated monday that fangs 
release would create a favorable environment for reopening 
talks on a 52 billion fiveyear loan package to china 
as fang left for britain a highranking member of the west 
german or parliament held talks with premier li peng a communist 
party politburo member li tieying was preparing for a visit to 
japan and a senior british official is scheduled to visit beijing 
next month for talks on hong kong 
rapid improvement in uschina relations is unlikely although 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater praised fangs release as a 
