<TEXT>
protectionism against imports costs third 
world countries twice as much as they get in foreign aid world 
bank president barber conable wrote to president bush 
nobody will benefit from fragmentation of the world trading 
system conable wrote the worlds poor stand to lose the 
most 
in 1988 the last year for which complete figures are available 
aid reached 48 billion the united states is the largest single 
contributor though it ranks close to the bottom when its own wealth 
is taken into account 
the world bank owned by 152 governments is the biggest source 
of aid lending over 20 billion a year 
if the industrial countries dismantled their barriers to 
imports the third world could raise its income by 3 percent 
conable figured the barriers take the form of import duties 
quotas that limit the size of imports and subsidies that the 
governments of industrial countries give to their own farms and 
industry 
conables letter dated june 18 was made available monday 
the next few months of 1990 may well be as crucial for freer 
trade as the last few months of 1989 were for freer peoples he 
wrote 
he said the leaders of seven governments whom bush will host 
july 9 in houston should break the deadlock in four years of 
worldwide trade talks this uruguay round has been stalled by a 
clash between the united states and the 12 governments of the 
european economic community over subsidies to farm products 
the bush administration wants exporting countries to end the 
subsidies they give to foreign sales the europeans want all kinds 
of farm subsidies reduced reducing subsidies given by the 
governments of industrial countries would help the third world sell 
its own products 
subsidies to farming are estimated to cost hundreds of billions 
of dollars a year to taxpayers and consumers of the industrial 
countries 
it is imperative that the interests of developing countries 
are fully represented in any agreement breaking the deadlock 
conable said 
agreement embracing all parties would benefit developing 
country exporters and importers especially in agriculture and in 
textiles and clothing 
