<TEXT>
the organization of reform rabbis broke with 
4000 years of jewish tradition monday and endorsed homosexual 
rabbis as qualified leaders of congregations in the united states 
and canada 
the central conference of american rabbis meeting for its 101st 
annual convention overwhelmingly approved a resolution urging that 
all rabbis regardless of sexual orientation be accorded the 
opportunity to fulfill the sacred vocation which they have chosen 
the conference is the organization of 1550 rabbis in the reform 
movement which has 13 million congregational members in the 
united states 
its an exciting day said rabbi denise eger the lesbian 
leader of beth chayim chadashim a primarily homosexual 
congregation in los angeles 
some estimates have said as many as 10 percent of us reform 
rabbis are homosexual 
the resolution was put forth by a 17member committee that 
adopted it unanimously after four years of study and debate 
the final resolution stated the committees majority position in 
affirming that homosexual unions are not on a par with 
heterosexual monogamous procreative marriages which were 
specified as the jewish ideal 
but a minority of the committee was able to insert a statement 
affirming the equal possibility of covenantal fulfillment in 
both homosexual and heterosexual relationships 
creating a traditional jewish home is considered a religious 
duty to the extent that sexual orientation is a matter of 
choice the majority of the committee affirmed in the resolution 
heterosexuality is the only appropriate choice 
in an interview before the vote rabbi samuel karff of houston 
conference president and a committee member said the committees 
unanimity in supporting homosexual rabbis had been contingent on 
emphasizing that distinction 
what emerges on the one hand is a desire to affirm support for 
our colleagues who are gay and lesbian and on the other hand we 
feel it essential to maintain our link to basic jewish norms he 
said 
jewish law embodied in the torah and other texts condemns 
homosexuality as an abomination but out of concern for human 
dignity one is permitted to violate the prohibitions of torah 
karff said 
about 500 conference members are attending the fourday 
convention which ends wednesday the conference originated in the 
united states but now includes reform rabbis worldwide 
a twothirds vote was needed to pass the resolution which 
stated it was an attempt to address the issue only in the united 
states and canada 
a 45minute debate preceded the voice vote with most rabbis 
expressing support and some calling for an even stronger statement 
others worried the resolution pushes the limits of judaism too far 
it will be an angle for enemies of reform judaism and those 
who are neutral to use this as yet another weapon as a challenge to 
our authenticity said rabbi clifford librach of congregation 
moses montefiore in bloomington ill 
reform judaism is the largest and most liberal of the three main 
branches of judaism in 1972 it became the first branch to ordain 
a woman rabbi 
the conservative jewish movement has had women rabbis since 1985 
but it does not openly accept homosexual rabbis orthodox jews the 
third major branch oppose ordination of women or homosexuals as 
forbidden by jewish law 
rabbi daniel syme national vice president of the union of 
american hebrew congregations said i view this resolution as an 
important baseline document that will serve as a basis for change 
in the jewish community as a whole 
the union which last fall overwhelmingly approved a similar 
document represents the 13 million members of us reform 
congregations there are another 100000 to 200000 reform jews 
worldwide 
the central conference which places rabbis with congregations 
warned gay and lesbian rabbis that their jobs could be endangered 
if they make their sexual orientation known and called for 
education and dialogue to encourage acceptance 
