<TEXT>
fang lizhi chinas bestknown dissident ended 
his yearlong refuge in the us embassy on monday and flew to 
britain after the government freed him in an effort to improve ties 
with the west 
the white house hailed beijings move as a humanitarian 
action that will improve uschinese relations 
fang and his wife li shuxian also a wellknown dissident flew 
from beijing to london aboard a us air force transport jet they 
landed at upper heyford a us air force base 60 miles west of 
london at 830 pm edt 
the couple had sought refuge in the embassy after the june 4 
1989 military crackdown on chinas prodemocracy movement 
the official xinhua news agency said they were given permission 
to leave the country for medical reasons after showing signs of 
repentance 
it said the move was in line with chinas policy of leniency 
toward those who participated in the disturbances of last june 
the us and chinese governments refused comment on fangs 
health condition 
but richard solomon assistant secretary of state for east asian 
and pacific affairs was quoted by hearst news service as saying a 
heart attack fang suffered last month was the facesaver that 
permitted the chinese government to cite humanitarian concerns 
in permitting him to leave 
a specialist flown to the embassy treated fang because he 
feared he would be arrested if he went to a beijing hospital 
solomon said 
the public security ministry said the couple was given lenient 
treatment after they admitted in a writing to having violated the 
constitution by opposing socialist principles and the leadership of 
the communist party 
in washington the state department issued a statement by fang 
and li in which the two said they remain opposed to four cardinal 
principles of the chinese constitution because their purpose is 
to uphold a political system of class struggle 
the two dissidents also said their purpose in going abroad is 
focused on scholarly exchange and research 
we will appreciate and welcome all activities which accord 
with the progressive interests of chinese society they said 
and moreover refuse to participate in all contrary activities 
whose motive lies in opposing china 
chinas decision to allow the couple to leave eliminated a major 
obstacle to bettering chinaus relations they deteriorated badly 
after the violent crackdown on prodemocracy protesters and their 
supporters which left hundreds and perhaps thousands dead 
the move clearly was intended to bolster chinas international 
standing at a critical time 
the us congress is debating president bushs decision to 
extend chinas mostfavorednation trade status which gives china 
lower tariffs on goods sold in the united states some members of 
congress have said china should lose the status because of its 
human rights record including the fang case 
also the seven industrialized nations are to hold their annual 
summit in july to discuss policies that include withholding 
government loans to china 
japans vice foreign minister takakazu kuriyama said the release 
created a favorable environment for reopening talks on the loan 
program 
japan had pledged a 52 billion fiveyear loan program to 
china but the plan was frozen after the bloody suppression of 
prodemocracy protesters 
on capitol hill monday senate minority leader bob dole rkan 
used fangs release to claim victory for bushs muchcriticized 
china policy 
it is a small but significant step toward the path that we 
want china to take the path of reason and the path of reform 
dole said it is also one bit of tangible evidence that president 
bush is on the right track in the way he is managing uschinese 
relations 
china has made several gestures recently toward repairing its 
image abroad since december the government has released nearly 
900 people arrested for taking part in the prodemocracy movement 
and it lifted martial law in beijing and in the tibetan capital of 
lhasa 
fang a 54yearold astrophysicist has been chinas most vocal 
and eloquent dissident since late 1986 when he supported student 
prodemocracy protests that winter 
the government claiming his speeches incited students to 
protest expelled fang from the communist party and fired him from 
his post as vice president of a major university but fang 
protected in part by his growing international renown continued to 
openly criticize the government and the socialist system 
until he and his wife fled to the us embassy fang spoke 
publicly both here and abroad about the necessity of political 
reform in china 
he pointedly avoided playing an active role in last years 
sevenweek movement even so the government accused fang and his 
wife a physicist of instigating the unrest they were charged 
with counterrevolutionary activities and placed on chinas 
mostwanted list 
fangs flight to the us embassy hurt his popularity among many 
chinese who said he and others who fled were unwilling to endure 
the crackdown with their countrymen 
in london on monday the foreign office said fang and li had 
been granted standard sixmonth tourist visas but declined to 
explain why the couple was going to britain rather than the us 
the foreign office spokesman said fang had received an 
invitation from the royal society britains oldest and most 
prestigious scientific organization fitzwater said fang had 
accepted a job as a professor at cambridge university 
fang is famous for his research in cosmology and blackhole 
physics he pioneered laser research in china 
</TEXT>
