<TEXT>
 
editors note as chairman of the senate armed services 
committee sen sam nunn dga is at center stage in the debate 
over postcold war cutbacks in military spending a man to be 
reckoned with heres a look at the man and his style a southerner 
often mentioned as a potential presidential contender in 1992 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
say his name in washington and you speak of 
power watch him closely and you witness a senator exuding the 
quiet confidence of competence 
question his ambitions and sam nunn will wince making you 
think hes just another georgian trying to survive the rigors of 
the capital 
as chairman of the senate armed services committee nunns power 
will be felt in the coming months as the senate weighs major 
military reductions in a postcold war atmosphere 
in a chamber filled with politicians nunn gives the impression 
of being more comfortable crunching pentagon budget numbers than 
gladhanding passersby 
studious and serious nunn is often mentioned as a possible 
presidential candidate in 1992 yet his most brazen political deeds 
of recent years have been confined to work within the democratic 
party to broaden its base among conservative voters 
nunn at 51 has attained a position in his political life that 
would bring a proud grin to the face of his greatuncle and mentor 
the late carl vinson legendary chairman of the house armed 
services committee and the only civilian to have a navy battleship 
named for him 
i dont think anyone on our side has figured it out says 
rep patricia schroeder dcolo marveling at the respect and 
deference shown by many senators toward nunn 
in a series of recent speeches nunn has already staked out his 
position in the allbutcertain fight over military spending he 
outlined his preferred level of spending and charged that president 
bushs budget is flawed with big blanks including the absence 
of an assessment of the threat to us national security a 
military strategy in response to the threat the future size of the 
armed forces how to meet required budget cuts and the need for 
major weapons 
bushs budget nunn said is based on a 1988 threat and a 1988 
strategy 
he said the congress would fill in the blanks if the 
administration doesnt 
the speeches came four months after defense secretary dick 
cheney had presented the administrations budget to congress yet 
nunn captured the headlines and set the tone for the debate 
hes very focused determined wellreasoned rational and 
tothepoint says rep john rowland rconn a member of the 
house armed services committee 
he wields his authority very judiciously and fairly and 
temperately says sen john warner of virginia the ranking 
republican on the senate armed services committee 
the defense budget falls within the purview of the armed 
services panel and as chairman of the panel nunn is one of a 
handful of lawmakers who have control over the largest portion of 
the federal budget 
nunn oversees the closeddoor crafting of the defense 
authorization bill by the 20member committee once the bill 
reaches the senate floor he is one of two managers who can ensure 
that an amendment is introduced 
nunns power was never more evident than last september when the 
senate working on the 288 billion defense spending bill restored 
600 million for president bushs strategic defense initiative 
program 
two days before the vote the senate had slashed 900 million 
from the star wars program an action that undercut nunns position 
in house and senate negotiations 
nunn pleaded with the senate to send a message to the house 
negotiators the senate answered the request 5347 and restored 
twothirds of the star wars funds 
on the other hand nunn widely viewed as nonpartisan took on 
bush and his nominee for defense secretary john tower 
allegations of womanizing excessive drinking and close ties to 
military contractors undermined towers selection and nunn led 
senate democrats in handing bush his first major defeat of the new 
term 
nunnpartisan complained senate republican leader bob dole 
of kansas 
yet the wounds inflicted over the tower nomination healed 
quickly and by september it was nunn who ensured that bushs 
military budget was adopted by congress largely intact 
sen john mccain rariz who fought nunn during the tower 
debate says that despite the contentious encounters nunn is 
very highly regarded by all of us republican and democrat 
robert costello the former procurement czar at the pentagon 
says simply that nunn has clout because he has brains 
yet georgias senior senator who has spent 17 years on capitol 
hill dismisses the suggestion that he wields the power in the 
military realm 
any time you want to legislate around here you have to 
convince an awful lot of people over a long period of time to get 
something accomplished so whatever power there is on capitol hill 
is widely diffused nunn said in an interview 
nunn learned early in his career how congress works when vinson 
hired him in 1962 to serve as counsel to the house armed services 
subcommittee on investigations 
vinson didnt make the process easy for his grandnephew 
dispatching one of the committees counsels john j courtney to 
georgia to review nunns law school transcript and interview his 
professors at emory university 
uncle carl waited until i got the actual results of the bar 
exam before he hired me nunn says 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900625-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the yearlong job provided a practical education in the workings 
of congress and the military as well as a sobering introduction to 
cold war politics 
the overall experience framed nunns approach upon his return to 
private law practice in his hometown of perry ga 100 miles south 
of atlanta 
it had a big effect on my reading and my studying and my 
retention of information that related to congress not just on 
military but in general nunn says 
after four years in the georgia house of representatives nunn 
sought the us senate seat left vacant by the death of richard b 
russell who chaired the senate armed services committee for 16 
years 
but vinson urged him not to run and telephoned some supporters 
suggesting that they withhold financial support says rep richard 
ray dga who worked as nunns administrative assistant for 10 
years 
vinson had reservations about his greatnephew taking on such a 
task and believed he should run for a lesser position ray says 
nevertheless nunn challenged thengeorgia gov jimmy carters 
appointee won the primary by a slim margin and went on to win the 
general election 
he gained a little seniority when he was sworn in in november 
1972 to finish the remaining months of russells term he was soon 
named to the armed services committee 
once there tragedy propelled nunn into the spotlight when the 
panels chairman sen john stennis dmiss was shot and forced 
to take time off to recover 
sen stuart symington dmo briefly assumed the committee 
chairmanship and relied on nunn to handle some of the panels 
chores 
one such project was a comprehensive study of nato late in 1973 
his report provided the young senator with his first national 
publicity 
issues surrounding the 16member nato alliance and military 
personnel proved to be the key for nunn as he staked out a 
conservative position on defense 
he picked his issues very well in the beginning starting out 
with manpower and nato both of them very hotbutton issues 
mccain says 
nunn largely favored increases in military spending during the 
reagan years but in march 1987 challenged the administrations 
interpretation of the antiballistic missile treaty to allow work 
on the star wars missile defense system 
nunn developed a reputation as hardworking bright and 
knowledgeable says john isaacs of the liberal council for a 
livable world but the think tanks director believes nunn is 
supercautious and unlikely to get himself out on a limb 
nunn rarely reacts immediately to the latest announcement from 
the pentagon or pronouncement from the white house choosing 
instead to craft a careful response that is often issued when the 
rhetoric has died down 
the cautious style comes from nunns father who was 50 years 
old when his son was born 
you could ask him a question and he might sit there for five 
minutes literally before he ever answered nunn recalls 
some people would go ahead and become so nervous theyd ask six 
more questions but hed still be trying to frame the original 
answer in a precise way in a way that was meaningful 
aside from his reputation as a defense expert nunn is also well 
known for his proficiency at golf his handicap is in the single 
digits with dan quayle now a member of the executive branch the 
senate armed services chairman has few rivals for the title of top 
golfer in the senate 
warner says nunns frugal approach has emerged on the golf 
course 
sometimes you have to hold him back from wading six feet out 
into a pond from recovering a golf ball the republican senator 
said 
recently nunn has ventured into campaigning for other democratic 
candidates and in the process his name has been bandied about for 
higher office specifically the presidency 
back in july 1979 nunn seemed to squelch that saying i 
think without any insinuations intended that the nation will not 
be looking for another georgia president in my lifetime 
but the call grew so loud that nunn was forced to announce in 
february 1987 that he would not seek the presidency he is 
unopposed in his senate reelection bid this fall 
with the 1992 presidential race not far off nunn refuses to 
shut the door entirely says he has no inclination or plans to seek 
higher office 
i dont rule out the possibility that one of these days ill 
decide that i may be more interested in exploring the presidency 
but i would have to feel that i had the substantive answers to an 
awful lot of the challenges facing america he says 
ill take another look after the november election and im 
sure ill be talking to a lot of people but based on the reagan 
rule ive got a lot of years left and i dont want to make any 
concrete statements about the future 
</TEXT>
