editors note hes no ordinary man of the cloth his brother 
is hardly a typical businessman one is a roman catholic priest 
the other a reputed mob boss here are two brothers sons of 
italian immigrants both of whom have attracted a lot of attention 
in new york city 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to his admiring flock the rev louis gigante is 
the priest who saved his ravaged parish hes the builder who 
stopped the urban death march in his south bronx neighborhood 
built new homes fought crack and crime 
to federal investigators hes the brother of vincent the 
chin gigante 62 the bathrobeclad reputed boss of the genovese 
crime family which has for years maintained its grip on new yorks 
building industry 
to the family of a harlem teenager accused in the gangrape of 
a jogger in central park louis gigante is the angel who posted 
25000 bail from his own funds so the youth could be released from 
jail 
to tabloid readers hes the priest who sat in jail for a week 
in 1979 because he wouldnt tell a grand jury about his prison 
conversations with reputed gangster james napoli a man he 
described as an old dear friend 
to one and all the 57yearold pastor is no ordinary man of the 
cloth 
iris gonzalez a member of gigantes parish who has known him 
for nearly three decades wont discuss how a man she so admires 
could have a sibling so infamous 
the fingers of the same hand are not the same she says 
there were five gigante children their parents immigrated from 
naples italy and settled in a coldwater flat in greenwich 
village 
the boys were athletic louis the youngest was an allstar 
high school basketball player while vincent scored in the boxing 
ring 
louis graduated from georgetown university on an athletic 
scholarship he attended st josephs seminary in yonkers was 
ordained a priest in 1959 and sent to puerto rico for two years 
in 1962 he was assigned to st athanasius church on tiffany 
street in the south bronx by the late 60s the neighborhood was 
in rapid decline and fires were wiping out the housing stock 
burnedout buildings were bulldozed leaving entire blocks leveled 
gigante turned to politics to fight the destruction running 
unsuccessfully for the democratic nomination for congress in 1970 
the next year he founded his own bruckner democratic club in 
1973 he was elected to a fouryear term on the city council 
during his years as a councilman the priestpolitician 
persuaded the government to allocate millions of tax dollars to 
rehabilitate the south bronx the money was funneled through the 
south east bronx community organization sebco a notforprofit 
housing developer 
the president and chairman of sebco is louis gigante 
the rev gigante brought a second spring to the hunts point 
section of the south bronx says new yorks cardinal john j 
oconnor who calls him the roman catholic churchs master 
builder 
he helped people there is more housing less drugs people 
get together they make a community says victoria serra who 
came to mass on a recent sunday with her mother rosa before 
drugs were all around us he led a march from door to door and we 
posted signs against drugs its a much better place now 
four years ago mrs gonzalez moved into a sebcobuilt apartment 
before youd be afraid of being here but now the 
neighborhood is changed 100 percent he helped people who had 
problems with drugs and alcohol people who were unemployed she 
says 
hes turned the neighborhood around says alberto negron 
28 glancing at the prefabricated wooden houses standing alongside 
crumbling brownstones 
st athanasius church is ringed by one and twofamily 
creamcolored homes with driveways iron security fences and 
gardens in contrast the area is surrounded by garbagestrewn lots 
with torched cars next to gutted houses the dismal south bronx 
that writer tom wolfe used as the setting for his novel the 
bonfire of the vanities 
it was a ghost town before father g built this and got 
parishioner support adds negron who was baptized in the church 
this neighborhood was terrible the houses were down 
everything was bad there was nothing says rsa serra father 
g is good i know him for 20 years the neighborhood is good now 
and he did it through faith 
nonetheless last year a manhattan grand jury began 
investigating whether the hunts point housing revolution may have 
included inflated bids and kickbacks to organized crime it 
subpoenaed sebcos financial records for the past three years 
court sources said 
sebcos offices are near the church rectory where the priest 
lived for years now he reportedly commutes in a cadillac or 
another of his six cars to several apartments in manhattan and an 
upstate country home sometimes he flies to a condominium in san 
juan puerto rico 
</TEXT>
