editors note she was truly an innocent abroad a new york 
city girl with little command of the french language and even less 
skilled in home repair that nothwithstanding she and a friend 
bought a 180yearold house in rural france when she set out to 
try to make it livable the doityourself way she found herself in 
a heap of trouble even running afoul of the law 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
first there was a bag hanging from our 
doorknob with lettuce so fresh from the ground a snail was still 
crawling through its leaves 
then a whitehaired country woman in her faded print smock and 
heavy shoes showed up in person to offer a promenade through 
the village to her vegetable garden 
as we made our way down the rutted dirt road she tried to 
teach a city girl from manhattan the names in french of the trees 
and flowers that i couldnt even identify in english 
i also picked up that day the misdirections that got me arrested 
by three gendarmes and hauled before the mayor for illegal dumping 
and so it went for the next two weeks me and my adopted home 
coming to grips with each other what one might call the 
gentrification of a tiny village in southwestern france and the 
frenchification of me 
an english friend and i had bought the house together in the 
spring of 1989 we did it on an impulse a whim for one thing it 
was cheap 
the 180yearold fourstory stucco and stone house with its 
red tile roof and electricity and proper plumbing cost little more 
than say an american minivan and taxes are only several hundred 
dollars a year 
so here i was a year later coming to claim my new home a new 
york city apartment dweller who cant find the start button on her 
own vacuum cleaner thinking all i needed to do for a house 
beautiful was find a flea market and proceed to buy french country 
antiques 
i was armed with a longago d in college french and a blue 
plastic tool kit shaped like a briefcase that i ordered from an 
upscale catalog the screwdrivers and pliers all had coordinated 
yellow handles and i had my 81yearold mother in tow to help me 
select the antiques 
the village has 500 residents a church a post office a city 
hall an elementary school a tiny grocery a gold statue of the 
virgin and a world war i monument topped by a gold chicken or some 
manner of bird the monument sits at the top of a tiny dirt square 
dominated by trees and large wooden geometic shapes that are either 
art or a childrens jungle gym 
the hub of the village is a big open sundrenched space that 
for some reason makes me think of gary cooper and high noon 
nothing happens there much except a couple of times a day when a 
merchant comes through to peddle olives or fish or shoes from his 
truck 
the houses crammed in close and facing each other on narrow 
crooked streets create a perpetual shade 
there is no restaurant no filling station the boulangerie is 
open only a few hours in the morning for fresh bread and 
croissants if you dont get there early everything is sold or 
reserved 
theres also the wine cooperative the raison detre for this 
village and all the others scattered through this area that cups 
around the western shore of the mediterranean from the lowland 
deltas south to the spanish border and from the foothills and 
craggy rock cliffs north to marseille 
each village cooperative has its own wine label bar owners and 
local residents alike come in with any sort of container large or 
small and get filled up from a hose attached to one of the huge 
stainless steel vats 
the area was settled by the romans and the mentality of living 
in something of a circle behind walls still prevails outside the 
walls the families of ceyras each own their own plot among the 
tilled and blooming gardens cascading down the side of a hill that 
drops off into the herault river 
their vineyards are generally beyond the village if they still 
till them the old vintners are dying off price supports for wine 
have dropped and the young sons and grandsons all seem to want 
paris 
so the english and other europeans from unsunny climes have 
discovered that these old farmers vacant and often neglected homes 
offer rare bargains in an otherwise outrageously expensive france 
never a farmers daughter i had nonetheless come home 
and it was a rough two weeks the culture shock had as much to 
do with unaccustomed labor broken fingernails and plaster dust 
that coated my hair like a lacquer as it had to do with rural 
living in a language i couldnt speak 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900625-0218 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
i fell asleep each night often in my dirty work clothes in a 
panic that my brain was going to explode rather than accept one 
more new word or sensation 
trying to buy paint remover is a major project you cant tell 
the salesperson what you want because you dont know the word so 
you wander around searching for something that looks likely then 
you get out the dictionary and start trying to read all the labels 
it took several days to get settled in with the proper gaskets 
for the generic wine bottles i finally located in a junk store i 
proudly took them to the winery carrying them in a wire rack such 
as milkmen used for home deliveries during the days when they did 
that sort of thing only to be shown not told that the loosely 
attached ceramic corks would leak unless i had a washer the amused 
attendant at the cooperative told me the french word rondelle but 
it took two trips to the hardware store to get the right size 
i learned to distinguish the slight difference between the 
french words for stove and hot water heater and i learned for the 
first time in any language the difference between plaster and 
plasterboard the plaster was what was in my hair 
things got better for my hair after i finally figured out how to 
ask monsieur boisseau my acrossthestreet neighbor if he knew 
someone i could hire to strip wallpaper and knock plaster off old 
beams 
it was that plaster that got me arrested my wonderful worker 
jean claude was knocking it off licketysplit and we were ankle 
deep in the powdery stuff as id fret about what to do with it 
hed repeat we needed a petite camion which i took to be a 
pickup he assumed i didnt understand but actually i had no idea 
how to go about getting one 
finally with the help of madame rieufregier the garden lady 
we decided to scoop the broken plaster into heavyduty fertilizer 
bags she saves and haul it in my spanking clean rented car 
mrs rieufregier told us where riverains residents could 
dump and i thought she said at the west edge of the village but 
at jean claudes direction we landed up on the east 
the gendarmes got there right after we did if you think 
american cops are bad chasing after speeders and illegal parkers 
when they should be arresting drug pushers and other manner of 
crooks just remember this story of three gendarmes wasting more 
than two hours with me in their van being grilled about my broken 
plaster 
they checked me through their computer to see if the car was 
stolen they asked me how much i paid the worker how long id 
known him then something else about pay when i said yes 
thinking they were asking if i would pay his fine i really got a 
grilling we went around that two or three times and they kept 
using the word fiche which normally is some sort of a bill 
when all the sudden my head went whoa it hit me that i might 
have an illegal immigrant on my hands or maybe i was supposed to 
be paying payroll taxes 
finally i just put my hands out in front of me wrists close 
together who knows the word for handcuffs but its a universal 
gesture they laughed and took me to the mayor 
not before i might add one of them asked me in a most acerbic 
tone il nya pas decologie en amerique 
you didnt have to speak much french to catch the sarcasm and 
pointed intent that theres no ecology in america meant 
flibbertigibbet foreigners bent on running around despoiling the 
french countryside were in for a hassle 
despite all my pratfalls the signs were encouraging 
the mayor laughed and shook my hand when i apologized for my 
legal transgressions the cops got a good laugh when i told his 
honor i was enchanted to make your acquaintance a stilted 
phrase straight out of french 1a 
several local men hanging out in a garage gossiping and smoking 
cigarettes teased me as i passed by about how i seemed to relish 
the local wine the caretaker at the cooperative gave me a bottle 
of champagne on my last day apparently in appreciation of what a 
good customer id been 
it all came i suspect from that promenade through the village 
with madame rieufregier all the old ladies were sticking their 
heads out their windows or making it a point to pass by and say 
bonjour 
madame rieufregier told me she had 70 years and that she had 
been born in this village one couldnt ask for a better sponsor 
than that 
</TEXT>
