<TEXT>
 
editors note cape cod that storied massachusetts retreat by 
the sea is still not without its charm but its a paradise 
threatened by the bulldozer and concrete mixer and local residents 
have begun to fight back 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
you can still drive to the corner of 
irving and scudder avenues in hyannis port and peek down at the 
whiteshingled kennedy compound nestled on rolling green lawns 
overlooking the broad expanse of lewis bay 
the neighborhood of large stately summer homes which includes 
a tiny red post office and a weathered dock at the end of the 
street looks almost exactly as it did the summer before john f 
kennedy was elected president 30 years ago 
but less than two miles away in downtown hyannis the landscape 
has changed dramatically and not necessarily for the better as a 
result cape cod residents have approved a sweeping new measure 
that they hope will curb helterskelter growth and restore some of 
the areas rural charm 
its a pigpen here says alexander theroux a yale professor 
and writer who has lived in west barnstable since 1974 when i 
moved here it was a lovely place 
route 132 once a pastoral road linking hyannis with the rest of 
cape cod is now a dizzying strip of fastfood restaurants 
billboards and shopping malls construction is almost complete on 
the enormous and controversial christmas tree plaza traffic is 
often backed up for miles 
elsewhere on the cape a flat sandy peninsula attached to 
mainland massachusetts by two bridges spanning the cape cod canal 
signs of trouble are everywhere 
contaminated shellfish beds ponds tainted by acid rain 
overflowing dumps ground water pollution 
the intersection at one corner in harwich is called the dust 
bowl by locals because of the swirling dust kicked up by a 
24acre construction site for an office and shopping center that 
has been stripped bare for two years 
i miss the tranquillity and independence that used to be out 
here says jack smith 65 the owner of jacks outback restaurant 
in yarmouth and a 50year resident of the cape i miss dirt roads 
and i miss pulling out onto main street knowing there wouldnt be 
anyone coming in either direction 
the population on the cape a 67mile strip that runs from near 
plymouth out to provincetown has swollen in the last two decades 
in 1960 the oldest town on the cape sandwich had 2000 
residents now it numbers 16000 and is still growing 
many cape cod residents weary of the minigolf outlets and 
kandy korner shops that have sprung up to accommodate the influx of 
tourists have decided its time to take action 
in march they approved the cape cod commission act which 
resulted in the formation of a county commission to regulate 
development on a regional basis up until now the 15 towns that 
comprise the cape have overseen development on an individual basis 
the 19member land use and planning commission is designed to 
control developments that will affect the region and protect 
critical natural and manmade resources 
the commission is not unlike other regional and statewide 
planning agencies around the country the adirondacks state park in 
new york lake tahoe pine barrens nj and marthas vineyard 
island off cape cod are areas with similar policies the california 
coastal commission regulates coastal development along the coast 
the cape cod commission also borrowed heavily from floridas 
statewide landuse policy 
proponents hope that the roughly 70000 acres of developable 
land left on cape cod will be more stringently monitored 
people said were sick of growth and development and were 
sick of the dismantling of cape cod says susan nickerson 
executive director of the association for the preservation of cape 
cod formed in 1968 when residents became alarmed over a proposal 
to cut a waterway into nauset marsh for oil tankers 
some of the statistics compiled by the group 
the cape cod population growth is 10 times the state average 
the number of housing units on the cape has doubled in the past 
20 years 
more open space was lost on the cape during the 1980s than any 
other region in the state 
the average home price on the cape has tripled just in the past 
decade 
about 6000 acres of shellfish beds remain closed an eightfold 
increase in just eight years 
most of those statistic apply to the socalled upper cape 
the communities around hyannis and to the west the lower cape 
which is the farthest from the mainland and includes more rural 
areas such as truro and the art colony of provincetown has escaped 
what one environmental activist called the schlock of the upper 
cape 
its a special place says nickerson a lifelong cape cod 
resident it shouldnt be turned into long island 
but real estate developers disagree they contend the cape cod 
commission will drive up prices for singlefamily homes and hamper 
the right of landowners to develop their properties 
the cape thrives on the building business says nick franco 
a cape cod developer for 17 years who has projects in hyannis and 
marstons mills the sad part is that there is a very little 
supply of land when you take that supply away from developers 
there will be a lot fewer homes and theyll be a lot more 
expensive a lot of the working people will have to leave cape 
cod 
but franco says its a misconception that all developers 
opposed the commission he voted for the commission he says 
because he knew he would profit from the sudden crackdown on 
development 
land is becoming dearer because of this franco says the 
day after the vote every one of my lots became worth 15 percent 
more 
environmentalists including former us sen paul tsongas who 
has a home on the cape dismisses claims that housing will become 
too expensive saying the real mission is to preserve the quality 
of life on the cape 
left unchecked cape cod would lose its character says 
tsongas who chaired a committee that recommended a moratorium on 
building on the cape its one of the few places in the country 
that really have a separate identity the concern was that cape cod 
was beginning to look like everything else 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900625-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
editors note no other spot in japan has quite the cachet of 
the ginza in tokyo its a paradise for hedonists an elegant 
shopping center a place where dinner can cost 800 a plate its 
also a place where oriental traditions persist where businessmen 
stay in touch with their local gods 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
thumping drums wooden clappers and eerie flute 
music draw the people of the neighborhood out to watch as 
shopkeepers parade a golden shrine through the streets oblivious 
to the honking horns of backedup traffic 
each year the ginzas busy shopkeepers put aside their work for 
a few hours to celebrate their local gods seeking protection from 
calamity for the worlds most expensive neighborhood 
the ginza is japans fifth avenue bond street champs elysees 
all wrapped into one its deluxe department stores cater to 
japanese matrons and a steady stream of tourists its bars and 
restaurants offer any type of cuisine in practically any imaginable 
setting 
it also is home to 3615 people who keep their traditions alive 
on land costing as much as 23700 a square foot 
by day the ginzas urban landscape is brightened only by 
luxurious window displays and weeping willows and maples along 
quiet side streets 
by night the neon lights of hundreds of pubs restaurants and 
hostess bars transform the district into a glittering paradise 
of female companionship good food and drink for men with deep 
pockets or hefty expense accounts 
no other spot in japan has quite the cachet of the ginza 
since the turn of the century this tiny district squeezed 
between the imperial palace and tokyo bay has been the place to be 
hundreds of optimistic shopping streets throughout japan bear the 
name ginza but none match its opulence or prestige 
four hundred years ago the ginza was under tokyo bay 
in 1603 one of japans most powerful shoguns tokugawa ieyasu 
moved to tokyo then known as edo he ordered part of the bay 
filled in 
under a later shogun a silver mint or ginza in japanese 
bequeathed the district its prophetic name at the time it was an 
earthy market and entertainment district 
after fires destroyed posh shops and villas slightly to the 
north shopkeepers moved into the ginza some have been there ever 
since 
the ginza itself has risen phoenixlike from ashes several 
times each time becoming more modern and western 
a fire in 1869 shortly after rulers in the modernizing meiji 
era declared that japan would learn from the west cleared the way 
for treelined avenues of londonstyle brick buildings 
just a few feet of those brick walls remain intact the 
westernstyle shops crumbled and burned in 1923 when a powerful 
earthquake leveled most of tokyo 
all but a few of the buildings constructed after that disaster 
were destroyed by us firebombing during world war ii 
today only a few prewar buildings remain and most of the 
buildings thrown up just after the war have been torn down to make 
way for modern structures most conform to an eightstory limit 
imposed to reduce earthquake and fire hazards and to give everyone 
at least a glimpse of sunshine 
ginzas night life its department stores and small shops all 
have an air of cosmopolitan elegance there are shoe stores with 
names like washington and america londonstyle tailors parisian 
brasseries and cafes and some 250 art galleries crowded into an 
area only about 1100 yards by 650 yards 
beneath the veneer of western commerce however the ginza is as 
japanese as its kabuki theaters 
in the morning shopkeepers fastidiously sweep in front of their 
stores wipe windows and splash the sidewalks to keep the dust 
down when department stores open to waiting crowds in the morning 
uniformclad clerks bow deeply and say irrashaimase welcome 
wellestablished department stores with names like wako 
mitsukoshi matsuzakaya and matsuya sell designer dresses and 
caviar but they also sell tofu sushi and dried fish and have tiny 
shrines or temples on their roofs to consecrate their businesses 
naohisa nagai 42 is the eighth generation in his family to run 
the echigoya kimono shop which has been in the ginza since 1800 
people have worn kimono for ages now they only wear them for 
special purposes such as ceremonies or in certain professions but 
even if the number of customers falls the number of shops like 
ours is also falling so we can stay in business nagai says 
on weekend afternoons when ginza dori the main street is 
closed to traffic families and dating couples crowd the sidewalks 
and shops continuing a tradition of ginbura or strolling on 
the ginza 
in the evenings sidewalk vendors left over from the times when 
night markets filled the streets still sell noodles and grilled 
rice cakes wind chimes flowers candy and toys palmists and 
fortunetellers wait serenely for customers 
beefy sumo wrestlers in robes and wooden sandals stride among 
suitclad businessmen and women in fancy dresses or kimono all 
headed for bars where a single drink could cost 127 or more 
in east ginza powerful businessmen and politicians gather in 
exclusive traditional restaurants called ryotei that charge 
800 a person or more for a single meal rickshaws carry geisha 
girls many aged but still elegant masters of traditional dance and 
music between the secretive tan stucco buildings with their 
miniature gardens at the entrances 
in recent years the ginzas less expensive wine bars and 
restaurants have drawn growing crowds of young japanese 
this is the best its ever been says yuji ishimaru who has 
run the ginza street association of local merchants for 31 years 
the young people really love the old atmosphere and the older 
men dont seem to mind being crowded out they want new generations 
to follow them 
the ginzas population mostly concentrated in its less 
glamorous eastern half has fallen from 8344 in 1970 to 3615 this 
year as inheritance taxes and high land costs forced shop owners to 
sell out leaving only a few diehards tiny shops sandwiched 
between modern buildings to fight land developers 
in his office ishimaru 53 proudly displays photographs of a 
local festival and a neighborhood visit to the nearby imperial 
palace to pay respects to the emperor 
we are all children of our local diety and of the emperor 
he says that remains very important to me 
</TEXT>
