after the revolution eastern europe is suddenly 
chic polish restaurants are favored by londons trendy set 
czechoslovak films play on primetime tv and three of britains 
hottest designers are chips off the old bloc 
edina ronay tomasz starzewski and linda cierach have taken 
inspiration from their hungarian and polish roots peasant 
braiding furtrimmed waistcoats and street styles from the cold 
war years to create collections that fuse an eastern sensibility 
with english swing 
although each designer has a distinctive style all are doing 
booming business among londons young and wellheeled 
eastern europe has been so submerged so hidden since the war 
that few people realize the depth of the design traditions said 
mrs ronay the daughter of a budapest family of restaurateurs who 
still makes regular forays home to shop and see friends 
hungarian embroidery is extraordinary the sequins and the 
waistcoats and the aprons are all so beautiful she said sitting 
on a cushion on the dark wood floor of her intimate kings road 
store 
patterns from an old book on embroidery discovered in a budapest 
antique store inspired the beading on evening jackets capri pants 
and skirts in red and black that are part of her collection for 
next winter 
pictures in a family album of her greatgreatuncle otto in a 
brocade and furtrimmed waistcoat inspired the trim on winter 
evening wear she said 
the 40yearold former actress started designing clothes just 
five years ago now she is one of britains best known designers 
with a reputation for combining the folkloric with the 
aristocratic her clients include actresses lauren bacall and 
charlotte rampling and the duchess of york formerly sarah 
ferguson 
