to wear fur or not to wear fur 
that is the question many new yorkers faced this last winter as 
animalrights activists mounted a major assault against the fur 
industry 
even as fur prices plunged and several retailers declared 
bankruptcy the battered furriers fought back round one has ended 
and both sides are claiming victory 
no question the animal rights groups have had a great deal to 
do with that decline declares george cave a national director 
for animal rights mobilization an animalrights group based in 
williamsport pa 
their tactic is to keep sales high but theyre driving prices 
way down to keep sales volume at the same level cave adds 
the movement has forced the issue to be in the media but it 
hasnt changed anybodys mind counters lili glassman a 
spokeswoman for saga furs an international fur marketing and trade 
association 
in fact the american fur industry has projected 1989 retail 
sales at 19 billion up from 186 billion for last season 
glassman says 
the fur industry has been in trouble but officials blame it on 
a worldwide glut of furs and warm winters in the united states and 
japan the two largest consumers of mink 
up until 1986 the fur business grew rapidly sales tripled in 
dollar volume according to glassman 
by 1987 farmers were overproducing and at the same time we had 
a stock market crash and the fur market slowed it was a natural 
correction glassman explains 
nevertheless the battle has been fierce 
antifur demonstrations were held across the nation especially 
on nov 25 a date designated by the animalrights movement as fur 
free friday 
that day bob barker host of the game show the price is 
right led 2500 protestors in a march down fifth avenue 
barker a longtime animalrights activist resigned as host of 
the miss usa pageant over its award of a fur to the winner 
four fur shops were vandalized in miami and fort lauderdale 
fla dozens of other cities were hit with protests including 
beverly hills ritzy shopping district 
the issue even went primetime when the television series la 
law aired a show that presented canadian trappers as brutes and 
showed animals being mangled in traps 
activists also adopted confrontational tactics there were 
reports of fur wearers being jeered at sprayed with ketchup or red 
paint and even having their coats slashed 
arm formerly known as transspecies unlimited says it doesnt 
condone violence 
it was a couple of isolated incidents cave says we dont 
advocate any kind of illegal activity 
the fur industry used the vandalism incidents for propaganda 
purposes and character assassination according to cave who says 
he believes the strategy backfired 
the fur industry also downplays the attacks on fur wearers 
there might have been a few incidents of spray painting more 
a scare tactic to make people think they might do it says 
glassman 
all this has changed the industrys promotional strategy to 
emphasize a fur wearers freedom of choice and the humane aspects 
of the industry 
when barker called the nations fur farms animal concentration 
camps fur farmers responded by saying that american fur farms 
receive the highest standards of care of any farm animals in the 
world 
an animals coat is a clear signal of wellbeing glassman 
said the animals must be taken care of very well in order to 
produce quality fur 
the industry also has attacked the animals rights activists as 
extremists who dont believe in using animals for anything 
including clothing meat entertainment and even aids research 
the fur industry is a matter of freedom of choice and these 
people want to take away their freedom of choice and their right to 
wear fur without intimidation says glassman 
round two is about to begin 
