us census figures for 1988 ranked south dakota as the 
seventholdest state with 14 percent of its population over 65 
florida was the oldest 178 percent followed by iowa and 
pennsylvania both 149 then rhode island arkansas and west 
virginia 
a congressional report issued last month said an estimated 15 
million older americans or 5 percent of all elderly are abused 
each year up from 1 million in 1980 only one in eight cases is 
reported according to estimates 
south dakota has about 120000 older residents skoglund said 
and last year fewer than 300 cases of abuse were reported 168 
were substantiated she said 
abuse can be physical psychological passive neglect 
selfneglect exploitation and abuse of power by professional 
caregivers skoglund said studies show elderly abuse primarily is 
inflicted by a relative most commonly spouses followed by sons 
and daughters 
skoglund said studies she has seen most of them done from 1982 
to 1988 also show that what has been thought to be the main cause 
of abuse caregiver stress really isnt most abuse has been 
found to be inflicted by people who depend on the older person 
one study showed that twothirds of the perpetrators were 
financially dependent on the victim she said fiftyfive 
percent were dependent on them for housing 
studies also have shown that those inflicting abuse usually have 
a drug or alcohol problem have a history of arrests are disabled 
or cognitively impaired or have suffered a recent loss of some 
kind skoglund said 
so you have a case where a vulnerable needy person is abusing 
a more vulnerable needy person she said 
south dakota has had five laws on elderly abuse on its books 
since 1986 and two more take effect july 1 by 1987 all states 
had laws governing abuse of older people and several states 
require reporting including florida skoglund said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

