</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the federal office of consumer affairs 
cautions that elderly people are more vulnerable to the extremes of 
summer heat because they do not adjust well to sudden increases in 
outdoor temperature 
such changes can strain the heart and blood vessels leading to 
heat exhaustion heart failure and strokes the agency says 
the danger signals dizziness rapid heartbeat diarrhea 
nausea cramps throbbing headache dry skin chest pain emotional 
changes breathing problems or vomiting 
any or all should prompt an immediate call to a doctor 
the agencys advice is to spend as much time as possible in 
airconditioned surroundings use fans to cool and circulate air at 
home wear loosefitting and lightcolored clothing also curtail 
physical activity avoid hot foods and heavy meals reduce the use 
of salt and avoid alcohol 
</TEXT>
