<TEXT>
the american invasion of switzerlands chocolate 
industry has left a bitter taste among some swiss pioneers of the 
confection and statistically its biggest eaters 
comments have been ranging from sadness to indignation in the 
wake of philip morris companies incs announced 38 billion 
acquisition of jacobs suchard makers of the two top swiss brand 
names toblerone and milka 
throughout this century toblerone with its typical triangular 
shape and violetwrapped milka have been synonyms of 
schokoladenschweiz chocolate switzerland 
it is almost as if a swiss entrepreneur would buy ford the 
weekly zurich sonntagszeitung editorialized after philip morris 
the worlds biggest consumer products conglomerate announced it 
would buy the worlds third biggest chocolate and coffee group 
milka cow is grazing on marlboro ranch headlined the basler 
zeitung in reference to one of philip morris cigarette brands 
and at toblerones hometown of bern the bund newspaper predicted 
popular indignation at the loss of this piece of switzerland 
will be great 
although toblerone and milka continue to be made in 
switzerland they will be part of an anonymous conglomerate with 
controls in the united states it stated 
even the staid zurich financial newspaper finanz und 
wirtschaft said the takeover would stir strong emotions 
emotions are not cooled by the fact that suchards owner klaus 
jacobs is a native of germany polls consistently show that 
germans are switzerlands least loved neighbors 
jacobs was the first foreigner to move into the swiss chocolate 
industry which is one of the worlds leading chocolate exporters 
sales last year totaled about 40000 tons to more than 130 
countries with another 60000 tons consumed domestically 
the swiss reputation in the field chocolate rivals watches 
cheese and bank secrecy as the countrys chief image makers dates 
to the early 19th century 
francoislouis cailler and philippe suchard began the worlds 
industrial production of chocolate another breakthrough came in 
the 1870s when daniel peter invented the milk chocolate bar and 
rodolphe lindt refined the product so that it melted on the tongue 
dario kuster director of chocosuisse the union of swiss 
chocolate manufacturers said in an interview monday that the swiss 
also were the first to push exports 
at the turn of the century they had an enormous lead he 
said up to 70 percent of the swiss production was sold abroad 
while foreign manufacturers focused on their domestic markets 
before world war i when other countries increasingly set up 
import barriers many swiss subsidiaries sprang up abroad 
an early awareness of what we now call marketing was a second 
important factor kuster said posters and ads were widely used 
already in the 19th century 
toblerone became a pacesetter in 1908 it registered with the 
federal intellectual property office and remains the only swiss 
chocolate that is patented 
it has become a special hit kuster said perhaps because 
the shape brings to mind the matterhorn or perhaps a whole range 
of untouched mountains 
swiss chocolate seems a must buy of even the most dietconscious 
tourists visiting switzerland they often claim that chocolate made 
in switzerland tastes better than the same brand made by a 
subsidiary abroad 
there is a good part of imagination involved said kuster 
but its true that the mix of cocoa beans the choice of milk 
and of course the swiss pride in quality are also factors 
switzerland supposedly is the biggest consumer at 25 pounds per 
capita annually but the figure may be misleading because it 
includes purchases by tourists in switzerland 
swiss sales abroad are in the quality range he said naming 
belgium as the countrys leading competitor in value 
exports last year totaled 200 million with west germany 
france britain austria and the united states the leading buyers 
respectively 
