<DOCNO> AP900625-0282 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
japan and the united states disagreed monday over 
specific plans for structural reforms of the japanese economy but 
a senior us official said progress was made and the talks were 
friendly and cooperative 
mondays meetings began a final round of trade talks dubbed the 
structural impediments initiative officials said they focused on 
japans plans for changing policies and business practices that are 
thought to impede imports and foreign investment 
the two sides remained apart on the issue of public works 
spending said the us official who spoke on condition he not be 
further identified 
japan has agreed at us urging to spend more on parks roads 
sewers and other public infrastructure both to stimulate more 
imports and to reduce the imbalance between savings and investment 
in this thrifty nation but the two sides disagree over the amount 
needed to significantly affect the trade imbalance 
us officials said earlier they were hoping for a 500 trillion 
yen or 322 trillion public works package for the next 10 years 
they also said they would like japan to promise to spend a certain 
percentage of its gross national product on such projects 
japanese officials however have indicated they favor spending 
between 400 trillion and 415 trillion yen or 258 trillion to 
268 trillion in the next decade on public works 
so far they have rejected the request to specify what portion 
of gnp they will spend on public works saying this would limit 
their ability to adapt public spending to changing economic 
conditions 
the us official who attended mondays talks declined to 
specify the figures being considered but he said we noted the 
current figure under discussion would not represent a significant 
increase relative to the size of the japanese economy 
japan also has pledged to ease rules on opening retail stores 
speed up processing of patent applications crack down on allegedly 
unfair business practices by corporate groups and revise its land 
use policies 
the changes are aimed at making the japanese economy more open 
to trade and foreign investment 
senior japanese officials speaking on condition of anonymity 
said the talks were relatively constructive 
i think the americans were satisfied about some things and 
dissatisfied about others one of the officials said 
on tuesday the talks will focus on us plans to do more to cut 
the federal budget deficit encourage savings curb excessive 
consumption and improve worker training and education changes 
aimed at boosting us export competitiveness 
washington has filled in the gaps and increased the 
specificity of pledges it made in an interim report on the talks 
in april the us official said he declined to explain specific 
measures taken 
the official said washington expects reforms initiated during 
the talks to have a noticeable impact on trade imbalances in the 
medium term about two or three years 
but he said the impact was likely to be more apparent in the two 
nations overall trade imbalances than in their bilateral trade 
accounts 
meanwhile in washington us trade representative carla hills 
raised the possibility that the july deadline for reaching 
agreement on a final report in the structural barriers negotiations 
may not be met 
hills said it may be necessary to hold another round of talks if 
all of the issues are not resolved at this weeks bargaining 
session 
we will continue to talk until the job is done if there needs 
to be another meeting so be it hills said during a speech to a 
trade conference sponsored by the institute for international 
economics 
failure to reach agreement by the original deadline of early 
july opens the threat that usjapan trade problems would cast a 
pall over the july 911 houston summit of the worlds seven richest 
industrial countries 
in her speech hills raised the spectre of a backlash against 
japanese imports in the united states if the current talks fail to 
expand foreign business opportunities in japan 
we simply must have japan open up faster she said japan 
isnt open and until we get that parity of opportunity we will have 
an enormous buildup of antagonism that creates a backdrop for very 
bad public policy 
japans trade surplus with the united states last year was 49 
billion according to the us commerce department its global 
trade surplus was 7692 billion the united states posted a total 
trade deficit of 109 billion in 1989 
</TEXT>
