<TEXT>
the southern co said monday it has reached a 
tentative agreement worth 300 million to settle a dispute over an 
energy sales contract with gulf states utilities co 
the agreement which is subject to federal regulatory approval 
would end all litigation between atlantabased southern and gulf 
states which is based in beaumont texas 
the dispute stemmed from a 1982 deal by four southern utility 
subsidiaries to sell 1 billion worth of electricity to gulf states 
from 1984 through 1992 
but in 1985 gulf states asked southern to suspend or end the 
sales saying its customers energy needs had fallen below expected 
levels 
southern said gulf states discontinued most payments in 1986 
southern subsequently stopped all transactions with the company 
southern contended that gulf states was required to continue 
accepting and paying for the electric power but gulf states 
argued the contract required good faith negotiations whenever 
changes in purchases were requested 
the case went before federal energy regulatory commission the 
us court of appeals for the district of columbia circuit and the 
us supreme court a separate suit is still pending in the us 
district court in texas 
under the proposed settlement southern will receive 75 million 
in cash 6 million new shares of gulf states common stock with 
very limited voting rights and a 160 million promissory note 
payable on jan 1 1993 
the settlement says that if the highest price of gulf states 
common stock does not average 1825 a share for five consecutive 
days through jan 1 1993 southern will get a cash payment for the 
difference between the average price and 1825 a share 
the agreement has a net present value of about 300 million 
southern said 
gulf states is putting its lewis creek power plant near willis 
texas up as collateral for future payments under the settlement 
were pleased that weve been able to resolve this contract 
dispute in outofcourt negotiations and come to terms that protect 
the longterm interests of our companies said southern president 
ed addison 
addison said it was too early to say what effect the settlement 
would have on southerns earnings 
gulf states chairman linn draper said the settlement avoids the 
possibility that litigation over the dispute would drag on for 
years 
this dark cloud has in many ways hampered our ability to look 
to the future draper said gsu management believes that 
removing this cloud at this time and in this manner is in the best 
interests of the company its shareholders and its customers 
draper said gulf states cash outlay for the settlement through 
1999 could be as little as 167 million 
the southern co is the corporate parent of alabama power co 
georgia power co mississippi power co gulf power co and 
savannah electric co at the time of the contract with gulf states 
savannah electric was not part of southern 
gulf states does business primarily in texas and louisiana 
